Revised '91 Figures Show
   M2 Grew 3.1%, Not 2.7%
Fed officials have said they were disappointed that the
money supply didn't grow faster, particularly in the latter
part of 1991. Critics of the Fed blame sluggish money-supply
growth for some of the economy's current problems.
   The revisions illustrate one of the drawbacks to relying
too heavily on money-supply data in setting interest rates.
They are subject to sometimes substantial revisions, as are
other economic indicators.
   The M2 measure includes currency, checking and savings
accounts, money-market funds and certificates of deposit
under $100,000.